lessons.content:
On a normal PC, plug in a USB stick and the computer instantly knows what it is - the device announces its name and type. Many parts on a small custom board cannot do that. A simple temperature sensor or an LED wired directly to the chip is **silent**: it has no way to say "I am here, and I am this kind of part."

So how does Linux learn what is on the board? With a **device tree**. A device tree is simply a **text file that lists the hardware on the board** and tells the kernel where each part is and what it is. Think of it as a parts list, or a seating chart, handed to Linux as it starts up.

You write this list in a file ending in **.dts** (device tree source - "source" means human-readable text you can edit). Each part gets an entry. Here is a shortened example for a temperature sensor:

```
sensor {
    compatible = "bosch,bmp280";
    address = 0x76;
};
```

The most important line is **compatible**. It is a name tag that says exactly what kind of part this is. Linux uses that name to pick the matching **driver** - the small piece of software that knows how to operate that specific part. If the name matches a driver, the driver loads and the part works.

This is also the number-one beginner mistake: a **typo in the compatible name** means Linux finds no matching driver, so the part silently does nothing - no error explosion, it just quietly doesn't work. The fix is always to correct the text, rebuild the device tree, and load it again. (For optional add-on parts, there are small patches called **overlays** that add an entry without rewriting the whole list.)

Recap: a board's parts can't announce themselves, so a device tree text file lists them; the compatible name links each part to its driver, and one typo there is the classic reason a part won't work.
